         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>204</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Only [with] (hol)ding (back) the water in the eyes [it is that] I leave you (now) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #b5 #b6 #b7 #b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1949"/></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... From the great pris(on) of the Saṃsāra I want to be released.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I (give away the ornaments) of householdership, the white garments ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [8d] Like the one giving up [his] followers [and his] (royal dignity) [9a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>174</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Because of that the gates of the senses must be guarded.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... must not be forgotten by him. The truth (he teaches?) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the attachment (will) certainly (disappear). (By) the virtues reached ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... must strive of oneself the kleśas ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">There is a great likelihood that this fragment and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht66"/> belong to one and the same leaf. The 4x11-syllable-metre (rhythm = 6/5) we have already met in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht64"/>. Since there is only one strophe number (8) preserved in this fragment, and because of the scantiness of both fragments, recto and verso side cannot be determined with any certainty. The translation, too, is frequently in the dark. Between the fragments there appears to be a gap of about 10-12 syllables.</note><note type="remarks">The original manuscript is missing, but was the remnant of the right side of a leaf, composed of two fragments and badly damaged. Probably belongs to the same leaf as <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht66"/>.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment" subtype="Tranliteration">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>94 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 5 <hi>tsälpmoymar</hi> is a writing error for correct <hi>tsälpoymar</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">Since <hi>empreṃtsñe – klä –</hi> constitutes a colon with six syllables, a form of the causative stem of <hi>ākl-</hi> ‘to teach' seems the most likely restitution.</note><note corresp="#b8" type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">Because of the accent, the only likely restoration is a gen. <hi>añ(mantse)</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
